{"id":"2301.13718","submitter":"Melanie Ferreri","authors":"Melanie Ferreri","title":"Naturally emerging maps for derangements and nonderangements","comments":"17 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A derangement is a permutation with no fixed point. We denote by $D_n$ the\nset of derangements of $[n]$ contained in the symmetric group $\\mathfrak{S}_n$.\nSimilarly, we denote the set of nonderangements, or permutations with at least\none fixed point, by $\\overline{D}_n$. We denote by $E_n$ the set of\npermutations with exactly one fixed point, and we use $\\overline{E}_n$ to\ndenote the complement of $E_n$ in $\\mathfrak{S}_n$, i.e. the set of\npermutations that do not have exactly one fixed point. We describe a recursive\nmap that gives a bijection between $D_n$ and $E_n$ excluding one element. We\nthen show the combinatorial description of this map and how it compares with\nother known bijections, and present an involution on $\\mathfrak{S}_n$ which\nexchanges elements of $D_n$ and $E_n$ excluding one element. This map can be\nused to obtain a map from $\\overline{D}_n$ to $\\overline{E}_n$ excluding one\nelement, and can be combined with a bijection from $\\overline{E}_n$ to $[n]\n\\times \\overline{D}_{n-1}$ to give a bijective proof of the one-term identity\nfor nonderangements.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 31 Jan 2023 15:55:59 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-01"}
